  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Aerospace Supercycle:</strong> Unprecedented backlog in commercial aerospace and rising global defense spending could drive faster-than-expected revenue and margin growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Faster Deleveraging:</strong> If PH uses its strong FCF to rapidly pay down debt, the interest expense decreases and equity value increases dollar-for-dollar.</li>
    <li><strong>Accretive M&amp;A:</strong> PH has a proven track record of acquiring and fully integrating complementary businesses (like Meggitt). Future acquisitions could boost long-term FCF growth.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cyclical Industrial Exposure:</strong> If a global recession hits, industrial production will slow, hitting PH's more cyclical segments.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Load:</strong> With over $9B in total debt, elevated interest rates could increase debt servicing costs if they need to refinance at higher rates.</li>
    <li><strong>Supply Chain Bottlenecks:</strong> Lingering aerospace supply chain issues could restrict PH's ability to fulfill its robust backlog in a timely manner.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the Intrinsic Value lower than the current share price?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">When a DCF value is lower than the market price, it generally means the market is pricing in either higher future growth (e.g., >10% sustained FCF growth) or using a lower discount rate than our 9%. Aerospace companies currently trade at a premium due to multi-year backlogs.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does the debt load affect the valuation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Substantially. In a DCF, we calculate the Enterprise Value first, and then subtract Net Debt (Total Debt minus Cash) to find the Equity Value. Parker-Hannifin's large debt pile directly reduces the intrinsic value available to shareholders today.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why use an 8% FCF growth rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">8% represents a moderation from recent margin-expansion-driven growth, but remains robust to reflect sustained tailwinds in aerospace and defense, along with PH's historically excellent operational execution.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

